{"type":"message","id":"6f8ee7ca","parentId":"4c2ab216","timestamp":"2026-05-31T17:35:19.322Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, but this doesn't fix the fundamental issue that greedy addition of k produces multi-term results. If k=3 and greedy addition gives \"1 + 1 + 1\", then \"114 × (1 + 1 + 1) + ...\" = \"114 × 3 + ...\" which is correct but ugly.\n\nA better approach: for k values, always try to keep them as single terms. Use multiplication or special decomposition for k, not addition.\n\nActually, the simplest useful fix: don't use greedy addition for k (the part that multiplies something). Only use greedy addition for r (the remainder part which is just added).\n\nLet me revert to a simpler approach: for small numbers < 114514 that are NOT in ALL_POOL:\n1. Try divisor approach (with proper parens when k_part is multi-term)\n2. If no divisor works, just return str(n) (don't try greedy addition for numbers used in multiplication)\n\nOr even better: the algorithm should ensure that any value used as a multiplier (k) is always a single number or parenthesized expression. This is getting really complex.\n\nLet me take a step back. For the academic route, let me use a completely different approach:\n\nFor any n:\n1. If n is in ALL_POOL_MEGA or n is very small (< 114514 and not expressible), just return str(n)\n2. Try 114514 division \n3. For the k part, try to decompose it such that k_part is a single term (no + inside), use nested multiplication\n4. For the r part, decomposed any way\n\nThis way, the k_part can be \"54 × 54 × 54 + 15 + 1 + 1\" but the whole expression is:\n\"114514 × (54 × 54 × 54 + 15 + 1 + 1) + r_part\"\n\nActually the issue was that 114514 × 3 = 114514 × (1+1+1) with parenthesized k_part is valid. Let me just test with the current fixes.\n\nActually, I think there's a simpler universal fix: wrap ALL k_parts in parentheses before multiplication, regardless of whether they contain + or not. This is technically always correct and doesn't require detection.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_2jRKYgOjXh8mHqsTAnyM9887","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nwith open('/root/.openclaw/workspace-son/stench_number/generate.py', 'r') as f:\n    content = f.read()\n\n# Simpler approach: always wrap k_part in parens for multiplication paths\n# Fix 1: small n divisor path\ncontent = content.replace(\n    'if \\\" + \\\" in k_part:\\n                            k_part = f\\\"({k_part})\\\"',\n    'k_part = f\\\"({k_part})\\\"'\n)\n\n# Fix 2: large number divisor fallback  \ncontent = content.replace(\n    'if \\\" + \\\" in k_part:\\n                    k_part = f\\\"({k_part})\\\"',\n    'k_part = f\\\"({k_part})\\\"'\n)\n\n# Fix 3: main 114514 path\ncontent = content.replace(\n    'if \\\" + \\\" in k_part:\\n        k_part = f\\\"({k_part})\\\"',\n    'k_part = f\\\"({k_part})\\\"'\n)\n\nwith open('/root/.openclaw/workspace-son/stench_number/generate.py', 'w') as f:\n    f.write(content)\nprint('done')\n\"\n"},"partialArgs":"{\"command\": \"python3 -c \\\"\\nwith open('/root/.openclaw/workspace-son/stench_number/generate.py', 'r') as f:\\n    content = f.read()\\n\\n# Simpler approach: always wrap k_part in parens for multiplication paths\\n# Fix 1: small n divisor path\\ncontent = content.replace(\\n    'if \\\\\\\" + \\\\\\\" in k_part:\\\\n                            k_part = f\\\\\\\"({k_part})\\\\\\\"',\\n    'k_part = f\\\\\\\"({k_part})\\\\\\\"'\\n)\\n\\n# Fix 2: large number divisor fallback  \\ncontent = content.replace(\\n    'if \\\\\\\" + \\\\\\\" in k_part:\\\\n                    k_part = f\\\\\\\"({k_part})\\\\\\\"',\\n    'k_part = f\\\\\\\"({k_part})\\\\\\\"'\\n)\\n\\n# Fix 3: main 114514 path\\ncontent = content.replace(\\n    'if \\\\\\\" + \\\\\\\" in k_part:\\\\n        k_part = f\\\\\\\"({k_part})\\\\\\\"',\\n    'k_part = f\\\\\\\"({k_part})\\\\\\\"'\\n)\\n\\nwith open('/root/.openclaw/workspace-